    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="la" resp="#AA">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name>Clodiae</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="patronym"><name><expan><abbr>P</abbr><ex>ublio</ex></expan></name> <expan><abbr>f</abbr><ex>ilia</ex></expan></persName>
                    <lb n="3"/><name>Secundae</name></persName>
                    <lb n="4"/><expan><abbr>sacerd</abbr><ex>oti</ex></expan> <persName type="divine" key="divaMatidia"><name>divae</name>
                    <lb n="5"/><name>Matidiae</name></persName>
                    <lb n="6"/>collegia
                    <lb n="7"/><expan><abbr>fabror</abbr><ex>um</ex></expan> et <expan><abbr>cent</abbr><ex>onariorum</ex></expan>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text from Garzetti (1991), with comparison to photograph</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>To Clodia Secunda, daughter of Publius, sacerdos of the divine Matidia, the college of craftsmen and textile-dealers [set this up].</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>As Garzetti (1991) notes, given that the measurements and appearance of this statue base and that of AE 1991.821 are almost identical, and they were found in the same place, both were probably contemporary (although the other inscription suffered re-use and erasure in antiquity). Garzetti (1991) also postulates that <ref target="EmpWor000692.xml">EmpWor692</ref>, although now lost, was likely in the same assemblage originally as it was almost dedicated by the same college, and the P. Clodius Sura of that inscription could be a relation to our Clodia (father or brother).</p> 
            </div>
